Here's the recommended approach using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

### 1. Create a custom `Window` subclass

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    private readonly NotesViewModel _viewModel;

    public AppWindow(Page page, NotesViewModel viewModel) : base(page)
    {
        _viewModel = viewModel;
    }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        _viewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

### 2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public partial class App : Application
{
    private readonly NotesViewModel _viewModel;

    public App(NotesViewModel viewModel)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        _viewModel = viewModel;
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell(), _viewModel);
}
```

### 3. Restore on first launch too

`Resumed` **does not fire on initial launch** (the sequence is `Created` → `Activated`). Load any previously-saved draft in your ViewModel constructor:

```csharp
public class NotesViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _draftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
}
```

### Key pitfalls to avoid

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| Saving only in `OnStopped` | Android's back button can jump straight to `Destroying`, skipping `Stopped` |
| Saving in `OnDeactivated` | Fires for dialogs/notification shade — the app may never actually background |
| Heavy work in handlers | Android enforces ~5 s ANR timeout; iOS has a background time limit. `Preferences` is fast enough; avoid DB writes here |
| Using `OnResumed` for first launch | It only fires after a prior `Stopped` — use the constructor for initial restore |
